  "prompt": "Will people without college have jobs in the future?",
  "response": "Yes, people without college degrees will continue to have job opportunities in the future, though the nature of those jobs may evolve. Here are some key points to consider:\n\n1. **Skilled Trades and Manual Labor**: Jobs in skilled trades (e.g., electricians, plumbers, carpenters) and manual labor (e.g., construction, manufacturing) will remain essential. These roles often require apprenticeships or vocational training rather than a college degree.\n\n2. **Technology and Automation**: As technology advances, there will be a growing demand for workers in areas like tech support, cybersecurity, and data entry, some of which may not require a college degree. However, these roles may require certifications or specialized training.\n\n3. **Service Industry**: Jobs in hospitality, retail, and customer service will continue to be available. These roles often prioritize experience and soft skills over formal education.\n\n4. **Entrepreneurship**: People without college degrees can start their own businesses or work in the gig economy (e.g., freelancing, ride-sharing, delivery services). Entrepreneurship allows individuals to create their own opportunities.\n\n5. **Lifelong Learning and Certifications**: Many industries now value certifications, bootcamps, or online courses over traditional degrees. Upskilling through these pathways can open doors to new job opportunities.\n\n6. **Changing Labor Market**: The job market is becoming more focused on skills and experience rather than formal education. Employers are increasingly open to hiring candidates who demonstrate competence, regardless of their educational background.\n\n7. **Government and Social Programs**: Many governments and organizations are investing in training programs to help people without degrees acquire in-demand skills and transition into stable careers.\n\nWhile a college degree can provide advantages in certain fields, it is not the only pathway to employment. Adaptability, continuous learning, and the willingness to acquire new skills will be crucial for success in the future job market.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
